HEADWORD: Burggrave
<hw>Burg"grave</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G.
<ets>burggraf</ets>; <ets>burg</ets> fortress + <ets>graf</ets> count:
cf. D. <ets>burggraaf</ets>, F. <ets>burgrave</ets>. See
<er>Margrave</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Germany)</fld> <def>Originally, one
appointed to the command of a <xex>burg</xex> (fortress or castle); but
the title afterward became hereditary, with a domain attached.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Burgh</ent>⟦br⟧
